y low). For comparison, my other computer\\u00a0speakers\\u00a0I\'ve used are Definitive Technology Incline\'s, Jamo P404\'s, and an open baffle experiment I built myself. And these compare surprisingly favorably for a fraction of those systems cost.<\\/p><p><strong>Pros:<\\/strong><br \\/>USB powered and small, pack up easily with great cable management to take anywhere.<\\/p><p>Clever design, I love the cable management and the volume knob thing. I love the aesthetics going on here.<\\/p><p>Sound: Great open soundstage with great dispersion (yes, even compared to the bipole Incline\'s), surprisingly good stereo imaging, they can outright disappear into the soundstage with a good recording.<\\/p><p>Fairly neutral sound but there is a slight lower midrange\\/upper bass emphasis. Off axis response is quite good except for the very upper treble.<\\/p><p>Detail is also quite good, particularly the midrange and lower treble.<\\/p><p>Bass is also well defined, quick, but not quite punchy, not just one-note bass like many 2.1 systems. I don\'t know what DSP magic JBL used on these, but they\'re wizards for getting a 2\\\" full ranger driver to sound this GOOD overall while also having as much bass as they do.<\\/p><p>Speaking of... Bass: yeah, I know, it\'s a 2\\\" driver, but with a frequency sweep I had some output at 50Hz, and I\'d say usable extension goes down to about 60Hz as a -6dB point. So that 70Hz rating is pretty conservative (I was honestly going to be happy if they even managed 80Hz).<\\/p><p><strong>Cons:<\\/strong><br \\/>Max volume is pretty weak, but for nearfield it\'s... adequate. There\'s a resonance around 80-85ish Hz that can be annoying on some songs, but in my experience so far that\'s been all of maybe 3 songs.<\\/p><p>Aux in is on the front of the\\u00a0speaker, which, though convenient, is bad for aesthetics if you\'re not using them via usb in my opinion.<\\/p><p>While the bass and midrange are way better than I expected, the upper ranges are a bit harsh when pushed hard and have a pretty steep roll off when you\'re off axis &gt;30 degrees (which should surprise no one for a 2\\\" full range driver).<\\/p><p>Since they\'re USB they count as a separate sound device and don\'t tend to play nice with whatever sound card your comp may have if you were looking to do anything fancy with them (as in adding them as surround\\u00a0speakers\\/center channel to an existing setup or adding a subwoofer), on that same note an aux out would have been nice for headphones.<\\/p><p>*No included AC adapter, hasn\'t affected me but worth mentioning.<\\/p><p><strong>Overall<\\/strong><\\/p><p>Overall, at $30, or even full price, these are excellent. Yes, I nitpicked the hell out of them and made a massive con\'s list, but if I were in the market for USB\\u00a0speakers, I\'d but these again in a heartbeat. I\'d love if JBL would develop a slightly larger version with a legit two way design and\\/or include a sub output.<\\/p><p>These are probably some of the best sounding computer\\u00a0speakers\\u00a0available for under $100, usb or not. Will others play louder? Yes. Will others play lower? Yes. Will they sound as good while doing either of those things? Not in my experience.<\\/p><p>TL;DR If you want USB\\u00a0speakers\\u00a0with way better than average sound that look great with some clever design, buy these.<\\/p><p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.amazon.com\\/JBL-Pebbles-Speaker-System-Silver\\/dp\\/B00JVX5SI6\\/ref=sr_1_acs_bss_3_1?s=electronics&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1536840738&amp;sr=1-3-acs&amp;keywords=speakers&amp;th=1\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\" rel=\\\"noopener\\\"><strong>Buy Here<\\/strong><\\/a><\\/p>\"},\"elements\":[],\"widgetType\":\"text-editor\"}],\"isInner\":false}],\"isInner\":false}]'),
